					<div class="col-xs-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
						<p>Your Wi-Fi might be fine for browsing YouTube & Netflix, but when it comes time to boot up your favourite game, consider plugging in the ethernet cable.</p>
						<p>Wi-Fi can be interfered with or disrupted by other electronics, metal, or even just small barriers.</p>
						<p>A hardwired ethernet cable, particularly one of high quality, will have an almost lossless and instant connection.</p>
						<p>There are countless guides online that will explain why ethernet cables are a better option than wireless.</p>
						<p>To put it simply? </p>
						<p><strong>All that interference from other networks, and other devices, won’t affect the hard-wired ethernet connection.</strong></p>
							<blockquote><p>Busy spectrum, lots of neighbours etc. the amount of wireless interference is higher than ever</p>
							</blockquote>
						<p>The distance between your computer or console and the router is fully within your control, so you might as well take advantage of the best possible connection.</p>
						<p>It isn’t the most exciting option, <strong>but the ethernet cable is a ubiquitous suggestion because it is the best solution.</strong></p>
						<p>If you can only do one thing on this list, our network engineers recommend this. A direct ethernet connection <em>will always</em> be better than any alternative.</p>
						<h3>But my router is in another room!</h3>
						<p>The first and easiest suggestion is to just buy a long ethernet cable and some cable organisation clips.</p>
						<p>It isn’t necessarily the best-looking option, and if your doors don’t have a lot of clearance around the frame you may run into some issues. </p>
						<p>Money no object? If you want to hide it fully, you <em>can</em> pay an electrician to run an ethernet cable through the walls.</p>
						<h2 class="mt-4">Can’t run ethernet? There are some backup options.</h2>
						<p>You don’t want to run a cable through the entire house.</p>
						<p>You’ve got a dog, a cat, a kid, or a housemate who would take issue with that.</p>
						<p>Luckily, we’ve got <strong>options</strong> for you to not become the most hated housemate.</p>
						<h3>Powerline: Internet over existing wiring</h3>
						<p><strong>Powerline products are one option.</strong> They use the existing wiring without your house to transmit data, and by simply buying and installing an outlet extension, you can connect an ethernet cable to the port.</p>
					</div>
