					<div class="col-xs-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
						<p><strong>A powerline solution’s effectiveness will differ based on the wiring in your home.</strong></p>
						<p>Newer homes with high-quality wiring will allow powerline connections to offer lower latency, higher stability, and higher throughput than Wi-Fi.</p>
						<p>Older homes with poor existing circuitry may have a worse overall connection through powerline than Wi-Fi.</p>
						<p><strong>The best way to check? Keep the receipts.</strong></p>
						<p>Unless you have far more tools or have wiring diagrams for your property, it is hard to gauge if a powerline connection will solve your networking issues.</p>
						<p>Mitigate your risk and make sure there is a return policy just in case!</p>
						<p>Hot tip: <strong>if you can afford to not penny-pinch with these, don’t</strong>. Either they work and you’ve got a great one, or you return them.</p>
						<h3>MoCA: Repurpose your TV Connection</h3>
						<p>An alternative to powerline is MoCA.</p>
						<p>MoCA stands for Multimedia over Coax Alliance, which was created to stream video.</p>
						<p>These lines used to be connected to most people’s televisions, but these days it’s likely you have never connected one if you opt for streaming services.</p>
						<p>Coax works similarly to Powerline, plugging into existing outlets within your home. </p>
					</div>
					<div class="col-xs-12 col-md-10 col-md-offset-1 my-4">
